Nov 10 2009 	Planes Trains and Automobiles	We visited the highly touted Venetian with another couple for a weekend getaway. We were VERY disappointed with the service we received from the hotel staff. We have stayed at many of the hotels in Vegas, MGM Grand, New York New York, Bellagio, and Treasure Island. ANYTHING that we asked for in our hotel was additional cost to our room. Simply asking for additional glasses was going to cost us $8.00 a glass (yes that is right, to borrow a glass from the hotel). We played for many hours in the casino, and there were stretches where we would not see a server at the gaming tables for an hour. We had to wait in line to check into the hotel for 1 hour! Then there was the Planes, Trains and Automobiles I had to take to get to my room. From the casino you have to walk across the entire hotel to the FIRST bank of elevators, up to another reception area, where you then have to walk (not kidding a quarter to half mile at least) to another bank of elevators to take you to your room floor. Which you then had to walk to your room. In all it took nearly 10 minutes to get from the casino to the room. It makes you never want to leave or go to your room. Just stay in the casino and spend your money. On a bright note the food was good, and our waiter the last night did the hotel a lot of good from our end because he is the only one I would even hire of the people we met. The room was nice and was about what we expected, still not worth the $250+ a night. FYI - Plug your nose when you walk in, they use an artificial smell that is pungent enough to make you sneeze and gag. All 4 of us had nasal problems by the end of the trip.	
Nov 10 2009 	Seen better days poor value	Not much positive to say, unfortunately. Poor value for money compared with the offers from Wynn/Encore, and the still beautiful Bellagio. The location suits me, close to Fashion Show Mall, Forum Shops, Via Bellagio Boutiques and the shops at Wynn. The Venetian was the hotel I stayed at during my very first visit to LV, so I re-visited out of nostalgia. I booked a King bed suite, and found myself talked into an upgrade to pool view when I checked in. Room on 25th floor, so I figured the view should be nice. Instead I found myself staring at two cranes working on an unfinished section of the Palazzo. Also realised pool view is no great shakes, unless you want to spend time in your room during the day, and look out of the window. Vegas is really about the fantastic Strip at night.The furnishings are dark, heavy and a bit oppressive, particularly combined with the poor lighting. Even with all the lights on (including the light in the cupboard) I still felt as though my eye sight was going. Little things really - separately no great problem, but in combination one kind of feels the enthusiasm is lacking. Cupboard door warped and jamming, silicone sealant in the bathroom curling away from the marble tiling, battery needed replacing in the tv remote, wobbly taps, switches etc. The toweling robe was not exactly generously cut (I'm not fat), moving walkways not working - my general impression was that money was being saved by cutting back on maintenance and luxury touches. Bit depressing, really. Slots tighter than a gnat's backside, piped music in public areas way too intrusive, and the offensive synthetic aroma everywhere is just vile. By day three I couldn't stop sneezing, and my nose started to bleed. At the Grand Canal shops and restaurants, a live string trio serenaded diners, but the poor musicians had to compete with loud piped music. The breakfast buffet in the Grand Luxe Cafe is boring, except for the fresh fruit selection. The daily resort fee (what is that - punishment for staying there??) supposedly includes a newspaper, to be collected at a desk near the ground floor escalator, but it was never open at the time I left the hotel for the day. I had a really super Halloween weekend, but will stay elsewhere next time.	
Nov 9 2009 	Memorable to the Last Detail	It’s been quite a while since I’ve written one of my infamous Las Vegas escapades, but this seemed like a good time. My lady and I packed up and hit the rode for probably the most special trip we’ve taken to Las Vegas. This time to the beautiful Venetian Resort and Casino!The best thing about this trip is I was able to keep it a secret from my girl until the very last second. She didn’t find out until we turned off of Las Vegas BLVD into the Venetian Parking structure! Needless to say…she was happy!The might be the best all around hotel I’ve ever stayed in. Aside from the ambience of this place that let’s you forget what continent you’re on, the prices for it all were very agreeable. I’m they type of traveler that’s always looking for a deal, but paying a little extra definitely paid off in the end. Where we paid for the hotel, we ended up saving in transportation, parking, and even amenities, it’s all right there! There was really no reason for us to leave the hotel, other than just getting out seeing the strip. The Venetian offers food and drink that accommodates all budgets, there are some of the best shows around right there on site and there’s one of the better spas I’ve ever encountered in Las Vegas.Walking through the Grand Canal Shopping area is a visual wonder. The whole area is made for people watching, enjoying a nice glass of wine or coffee, or just sitting on a bench and admiring the sky painted on the ceiling or the neighboring works of art that paper the plaza. One of our favorite ways to spend our free time was in St Mark’s Square. It’s a replica of the real one in Venice…minus the pigeons. There, the Venetian Trio entertains the crowd by playing music and interacting with the audience. They’re always very friendly and there’s no pressure to leave a tip for them, however I couldn’t resist leaving them money every time I walked through.The rooms are incredible! The hotel is all-suite, so there’s no such thing as a bad room. We got the basic luxury suite and were very impressed. King sized bed with some of the most comfortable pillows I’ve ever slept on, sunken living room with sectional sofa and work station, all marble bathroom with tub big enough for two and separate glass enclosed shower area and not to mention…three flat screen television sets! Need I say more? It was perfect down to the last detail. It was a good thing that everything we needed was either in the hotel or close by, because we never wanted to leave that room.If you’re looking for a one of a kind hotel experience; whether you’re a family, with you’re lover, or just flying solo, The Venetian has got your number.	
