Nov 1 2009 	A mixed review	My stay at the Venetian didn't start well, but it improved as I got used to the place. Didn't have to wait too long to check in, but we were not given clear directions to get to the guest elevators (and it is a big, confusing, noisy place when you first arrive). So we ended up in the middle of the casino with our suitcases, completely lost. Eventually got to our suite, which was on the 26th floor, so had a great view. However, the decor looked dull and dingy, the sofa cushions were worn, had buttons missing and needed replacing, and the room was not clean. There was a thick layer of dust on the dining table, and debris (beer can/litter/room keys) left over from a previous guest. The two things I disliked most were the awful sickly smell in the casino and shopping mall, and the poor lighting in the suite. I have never before stayed in a hotel where the bedside lights for a double bed were not controlled independently. Either both bedside lights were on, or neither of them. The lighting in the suite was also inadequate.On a more positive note, the bathroom was well-lit and spacious, with lots of towels and toiletries. Didn't see the point of the bathroom TV as you couldn't see it if you were using the bath! One of the highlights of the trip was the pool area, which was fantastic, and the robes in the wardrobe were useful for going to and from the pool. In the mornings, we collected coffee and pastries from Tintoretto's Bakery in the Grand Canal area, which we took back to our room. We also had a good meal at the Grand Lux cafe, which serves very large portions.The decor in the Venetian is great fun, very luxurious and OTT, but you can see most of it without actually having to stay there. So I think I would look elsewhere for somewhere to stay if I return to Vegas.	
