Oct 29 2009 	I'm in love with this hotel!! Best stay ever.	Booked the room via a travelagency and got a really good price for it. When we arrived, we got an upgrade with a bit of a view. We could see the Treasure Island, the pool area and the mountains. Unfortunately, there was a contruction right in front of us, but we didn't mind. Our room was on the 22nd floor, so the view was quite good!The hotel itself is huge, everything takes long, getting from A to B. But when you're on a vacation, you have time, don't you?Oh, and the scent.. I don't know what it is, but I loved it!! You could buy it at their shop, we didn't do that, and I regret it. It's not in the rooms, but as soon as you get in the hotel, casino or shopping areas, it is everywhere. Well, I loved the scent, but I can imagine, that some people might not like it.We only had breakfast to go from the coffee shop on the 2nd floor. Coffee bean and tea leaf. Good coffee fo agood price. But don't touch the bananas and yogurts - that makes it expensive right away..The staff is great, very helpful. The concierge great.Next time in Vegas, I defenitely want to stay in this hotel!By the way: On our last night on the trip we stayed at the Ritz in LA (MArina del Ray) and that was quite disappointing, if you've been here before.. The Venitian is just WOW!!!	
Oct 29 2009 	Very Pleased	Stayed here the 2nd week of October 2009. I was very pleased with the Venetian, it seemed to be right on the money for what I was looking for. Booked through expedia and got a ridiculously low rate, also signed up for their Grazie club online and got the free 15 in slot play. The rooms were great, no sign of aging or wear in my room or my parents adjoining room either. Bathroom was marvelous, bed was very soft with great blankets (usually a problem since my husband is the air conditioning king), nice sitting area with table and sofa so you could plan your day. However, don't count on any fridge space, it's loaded with expensive alcohol that you can't move or else you pay for it (sensored for tampering), I didn't check into if you could get a fridge sent up, just don't count on the one in the room. The provided soaps in the bathroom smell awesome, use them!At check in I was provided with coupons, I used 2, free slot play and free drinks at Lavo. The free slot was a 30? dollar credit that I won/lost with for about an hour and then cashed out when it was at 15, can't complain about free money! The Lavo bar was very nice and classy, just showed up with the coupon and was able to get 2 drinks, just left a tip, worked easily and who can complain about more free stuff? You have to go to the Grazie desk to get your free play and card, make sure you go at a random time (late, like 2 am) if you don't want to wait in line, if you see no line in passing go then because it wont stay that way.Only thing that I have to agree with the complainers on is the smell in the casino, when I first arrived I thought I would choke but by the 2nd/3rd day I was usto it. And the rooms don't smell at all so don't fret!	
Oct 28 2009 	Five Stars in virtually every way! Spectacular Hotel!	My wife and I stayed at the Venetian Hotel and Casino in Las Vegas, NV in October of 2009. The Hotel is absolutely amazing in just about every way. Reading some of the reviews here, people said it was too big, or had too many rooms for the staff to really care about you, but that is being very petty. We had no trouble at all with the staff and unless you are a grouch then you understand that in Vegas bigger is better. Our suite was big and clean. The bathroom had a tub and glass stand up shower, a large vanity with two sinks, the toilet was separated with a door. The bathroom also had a small TV and came with a makeup mirror and blow dryer. The bedroom area had a wonderfully huge bed that was amazing to sleep on and a wall mounted flat screen TV. The living room area had a big couch, coffee table, TV stand with another flat screen, mini bar, safe, office area, fax machine, internet access, and seating for three at a small dining table. Our window had remote controlled shades and although we had a room with our window facing opposite the strip (you could see parts of the roofs of the Shopping area), we had an amazing view of the mountains and houses that were lit up at night. Maid service was no problem, plenty of towels, etc. We didn't get room service and we didn't use the mini bar at all. The mini bar prices were obviously very high ($7 for a Heineken, $5 for a small Sprite). We had a safe which was convenient and you are able to make your own 4 digit code for it. We were offered a view of the Strip as an upgrade but declined it because they wanted $35 extra per night.As for the Hotel, Casino, and Shops making it seem like the entire complex was too large, we really didn't feel that way. We did get lost for a minute, but there are plenty of workers who can help you find your way around. The waitresses at the casino are always around to offer you drinks on the house and the dealers will advise you if you need help at a table game. They have a poker room and slots that go from a penny to $100 per spin. Most of the table games are just like any other strip casino and there really wasn't any night that was overly crowded in the casino (it was October).The Shops are for the most part on the high end of the price range, but if you are willing to spend money you can get some great stuff. They have plenty of clothing, jewelry, watches, antiques, books, food, etc. They also have some reasonably priced items here and there, but don't be shocked because it is a high end Hotel, so there are clothing stores where a shirt will cost $300 and a pair of shoes might cost $500.There is also a Gondola ride inside (and outside). They have people who stay in character as they guide you on the ride and even sing. Our woman had a very nice voice and was very friendly. The ride takes about 15 minutes or so and there usually is only a small wait to get to ride one. There are also a few high end nightclubs in the Hotel (on Fri and Sat they had very long lines to get in!)Part of the hotel has a Wax Museum which we visited. It was nice and fun to take pictures throughout but it didn't seem to be that big. We went early in the morning and were one of the first people in and it only took us less than 30 minutes to go thru the whole thing.The restaurants are plentiful inside the Venetian (and the adjoining Palazzo). We ate at Dal Toro's, the Grand Lux Cafe and Emeril's Stadium as well as a bunch of little eatery's like the deli's and doughnut places. The restaurants prices aren't really that high. At the three above named places the bills were well under $100 dollars for two meals, sodas, and appetizers (we didn't get alcohol with our meals, as alcohol can be very expensive anywhere on the strip!!).Overall the Hotel/Complex was clean, not too busy and amazingly beautiful. Everywhere you look, it's a sight to see with columns, statues, painted ceilings, wonderful architecture, waterfalls, etc.My wife had a massage at the Venetian's Canyon Ranch Spa. She loved it. It cost $160 for 50 minutes and she gave a $20 tip. The Spa stuff was very high priced, but they had virtually everything you could want from massages, to facials, haircuts, makeup, waxing, etc. They also had a full gym, rock wall, and personal trainers for additional prices.The pool area was nice (I believe there are several pools, but we visited just one). There were a ton of lounge chairs, towels and some cabanas. The pool is large, but goes to just a depth of 4 feet so there is no slide or diving. There are also a few hot tubs.As with any strip hotel, be prepared to give everyone a tip for anything they do from bellhops, to waitresses, to bartenders, cabbies, dealers, doormen.You can always get a cab as there are lines of them waiting to pick you up as soon as you walk out of the door and in every store that you walk into people there are very friendly (obviously they want to make commissions on sales), but none seemed too pushy.Well that's my take on the Venetian. I would give it 5 Stars in just about every way and we really had no major issues at all.	
