Oct 7 2009 	Everything under one roof	A friend and I stayed here for two nights with a special Club Grazie rate. Check in was smooth. We received a room in the Venezia section overlooking the Pool Garden. The whole hotel and casino smells clean for the most part and does not reek of cigarettes like many Vegas strip properties. Really enjoyed the spaciousness and elegance of our room. Took advantage of the nice tub. I love this hotel for the way they stand out above the other ones in the area. There's not many places you can go that have gone to these lengths to replicate Old Italy with its archways, romantic lighting, beautiful paintings, and gracious service. I was greeted by name among most everyone. Room service, albeit expensive, was prompt, professional and courteous. The bellmen took our luggage from the taxi and brought it to us once we got to our room, something I've not had during previous Vegas stays. Many people have complained here about the huge layout of the hotel. It is confusing, but not as bad as other hotels. Whenever you stay in Vegas or a large all inclusive beach hotel you will more than likely have mazes to contend with to get from one place to the other. It's just something you live with, or simply stay home.I have two major complaints. One is that they do not have any kind of vending machines to buy a coke on the hotel floors. This is probably because they don't want the mass market hotel image, but it would be nice to have some sort of closed off vending area on each floor for these conveniences. Of course they want you to order it from room service, or walk through the mazes to get to a sundry shop. At 2am you just want to relax and not have to worry about putting clothes on to go get a beverage or small snack. The in room servibar does not have any refrigeration for its drinks. This means that they sit in a hot drawer or cabinet for probably weeks before someone succumbs to the temptation to indulge. Then there is the issue of cocktail waitresses. I don't care if you are a whale or playing penny slots, people need to have refreshments while they game or they will leave. I had to get up and find a waitress to bring me a drink while I was playing slots, and that should never happen. There really is no reason to leave the resort unless you want to experience shows/entertainment located elsewhere. There's plenty to do, and Madame Toussad's is a must.	
