Oct 3 2009 	Venezia Hotel at the Venetian Las Vegas NV -- Not As Advertised	We stayed here Sep 27 - Sep 30, 2009. Received an email offering one great rate at the Venezia, which is part of the Venetian (the other part is Palazzo). It used to be that the Venezia was more expensive than Venetian, offered better services, rooms, etc. More of a boutique hotel. Our rate was $49 per night or $79 for a guaranteed view. The email said (and so did their web site) separate check-in lobby. We've stayed at the Venetian many, many times but never wanted to pay the additional $50 a night for the Venezia. I'm so glad we never did.We had a car, so parked in the garage. What a circus to get to check-in. First of all you take the elevator in the parking garage to level 3. Then you get into another elevator to go to the Venezia Lobby (private check-in, remember?). Then you walk to the private lobby and read the sign at the check-in desk that says &quot;We no longer operate this check-in, please proceed to Venetian check-in.&quot; OK, now I'm a bit miffed, because we've walked all around the world and still have to go back to the Venetian check-in, which means going around the world again!!!! Of course the Venetian has a long line to check-in, which moved pretty fast, really. After check-in, we had to take an elevator to the 10th floor (Venetian lobby), then get on another elevator to our room. What a pain in the rear. From the parking garage that means 3 elevators to get to the floor with your room. While my spouse waited in line, I went to the concierge desk and told them about the desk being closed--and she couldn't have cared less--&quot;do you want to speak with a manager?&quot; was the response. I told her we'd talk to a hotel manager when we got through the long line to check-in. When we got to the check-in clerk, she was most apologetic, saying they had closed the Venezia desk several months ago. I told her that the email and their web site advertised the private check-in. She said they had within the last few days taken it off their web site because of the same complaints, but was unaware of the email offers that said &quot;private check-in.&quot; She was also unaware of the signs in the parking garage that showed &quot;Venezia Check-in&quot;. She offered a late check-out which we accepted.Now to the room. The room we had was very worn. Cushions on the sofa were broken down.--flat, and I mean totally flat, on the outside edge. No cushion at all. There was a pumpkin seed in the middle of the floor when we got there and it was still there when we left. The table, which had a nice glass top, was very worn underneath--wood that was lifting up and cracked. The mattress was definitely very old, although not uncomfortable, but definitely not the nice pillow-tops that all the hotels in Vegas now have. No bedspread or comforter on the bed--just triple-sheeted with a blanket between the two top sheets. Three SMALL pillows on the bed. Didn't even cover the width of the bed. Not very pretty looking. Bathroom. Supplies were in short supply. One bar of soap. One small bottle of bath gel, one small bottle each of shampoo, conditioner and lotion--all bitter orange and smells wonderful. If you use the bar soap for your hands you have none for the shower. I left a note (and a $5 tip) for housekeeping. They did put out 3 more bars of soap, but NEVER replenished it. The bathroom supplies were definitely smaller bottles than the bottles (which were very pretty) at the Venetian (we stayed at the Venetian in July 2009). The printer on the desk was out of ink and never printed our &quot;welcome letter&quot;. I wonder how many were piled up in the printer's memory. Some of the light switches never turned on any lights, so I wonder if light bulbs were burned out. For the $79 we paid, the room was OK, but definitely NOT UP TO THE QUALITY we expected. Would I stay there again? Possibly if the price is right. Our offer is still good through the end of the year, as many times as we want, but, I was expecting a really nice experience. Unfortunately, that did not happen. We’ve paid a lot more for a lot less; and we’ve paid the same for a lot more. Like I said, it is totally inconvenient if you have a car--it requires 3 elevator waits and 3 elevator rides to get to your room. Security is pretty good though, once you get on the Venezia lobby floor, there is a security guard 24-hours a day, requesting to see your room key before you can go to the elevators to the rooms. All in all, we had a good time, but I was terribly disappointed in the quality of the room, the cleanliness of the room, and the short-supply of toiletries.The pool and gardens area is very nice, small, but very pretty and is suppose to be private to Venezia customers, but nothing stops the folks who stay at the Venetian or Palazzo from coming into the Venezia lobby and going to the pool and gardens. Once you stay at the Venezia, you know that. The lobby is absolutely beautiful. It's just a shame that they closed it and now require everybody to go through the looonnnggg lines at the Venetian. So, just beware if you get a really good deal from Venezia. I would recommend the Venezia to my friends with the stipulations that it's very dated, needs to be refurbished, but at least the rate they offered reflects that.	
