Sep 10 2009 	Nice and friendly hotel.	Flew to Vegas on Southwest on Sept. 6th. Wanted to avoid the outrageous charge for a Sat. night stay. Stayed from Sun - Wed. in a Bella Suite in the Venezia tower for about $80 a night. Joined the Grazie players club on my previous trip and even though I only played slots briefly, I received an e-mail with this great rate offer. I tried to book on line as there was a rate of about $50 per night, but it wouldn't go through, so I called the Venetian. I'm glad I did because I learned that the lower rooms in the Venizia look at the parking garage. The room we had was on the 12th floor and had a great view of the airport and the mountains. We checked in at about noon. It did take about 45 minutes for the bell hop to bring our bags to our room, which seemed a bit long even for a big hotel. You do need to be in the room to receive your bags. The bell hop was very friendly with regards to giving tips for getting around the hotel. The hotel and casino were relatively easy to get around if you read the signs. The room was beautiful and clean. The bed was comfortable, but not great. The staff we met were very friendly and their is security everywhere. Make sure you have your key with you as they ask to see it all day long before going to the halls that lead to your room. The casino was nice but drink service was slow and the slots were very tight, which was expected being Labor Day weekend. This seemed to be a reoccuring theme at many of the casinos on this trip. We did not use the pools, but walked around the main pool area. There are a lot of chairs, but many were not getting sunlight at 11 am. The Venetian seemed to have a large number of kids, but the hotel was quiet with regards to not having kids screaming or hearing people partying in the hallways. As with most hotels in Vegas, the walls between rooms are thin, but it's not bad.We did see Zumanity, which I booked before I left for Vegas and the show appeared to be sold out, so I'm glad we booked before we left. The show is very good, but is an adults only and you need to be open minded and not offended easily as it is very sexual and the performers do get the audience involved. We booked tickets for Wayne Brady and Legends though tickets for tonight, which is a great place to get discounted tickets for the shows that day or the next. Wayne Brady was very funny. Legends has good impersonators, but it was only ok. I will say that none of the venues appeared to have a bad seat as the theaters were small. We also saw Titanic at the Luxor on the last day of our trip. We both enjoyed it, but do not think it's worth the $30 per ticket that was paid at the box office. The box office at Luxor by the Titanic exhibit was also very slow. They has 3 people working it, but only 1 seemed to really be working.I usually only eat at one buffett per trip, but on this one we ate at three. The buffett at Treasure Island was descent. The buffett at Paris was very disappointing as the it was about a 45 minute wait to get in for lunch and the food was bland. The Spice Market buffett at Planet Hollywood was excellent as always. With regards to to other restaurants; Margarittaville was great as always with regards to food and drink and the atmosphere. BLT at the entrance to the Mirage has good BBQ nachos and shakes, but the hamburgers are not worth the price. Happy hour at the Cantina in the Shops at Venetian had good drinks and food.Before I left for Las Vegas, I paid $10 per person for the early bird check in on Southwest, so I could make sure I would sit next to who I traveled with and not be in Vegas having to make sure I'm at checking in exactly 24 hours before my flight. The early bird worked out well as we were A20. The concierge at the Venetian checked us in and printed our boarding pass and it did not cost anything, but I did tip her $5. Next to the concierge desk at the Venetian is a company that charges $20 per person and you can check your bags there if you are flying Southwest and I forget what other airlines. They will also print your boarding pass when you check in your bag. The next time you see you bags is when you get off the plane at your destination. I feel the service is worth it if you are flying out of Vegas late because then you do not have to worry about going back to your hotel just to get your bags before heading to the airport. We checked our bags in at the Venetian, and then took the monorail to MGM and and explored the south side of the strip. When we had to go to the airport we took a taxi from Mandaly Bay, which is where we happened to be and the taxi ride was cheaper.Overall, Vegas was fun as always and I would stay at the Venetian again if I could get a good rate on the room.	
