Aug 28 2009 	Venetian with a view of the Mirage Treasure Island and Trump Hotel.	We read all the comments from other travellers on tripadvisor what and what not to do during our trip and it was very helpful. For instance we did ask the taxi driver not to take the freeway to our hotel, so therefore from the airport to venetian hotel cost $22 excluding tips. We were advised on the tripadvisor from other fellow travellers to tip $1/bag for the taxi driver. We did noticed a difference in fare when we were going home from the venetian to the airport on Thursday August 27th, 2009, the husband deliberately didn't ask the taxi driver to avoid the highway and the fare ended up $29 excluding tips for the baggage handling. So now we know the difference and we will definately insist the driver to talk the alternate route other then the freeway.The husband signed up for the players club membership at the Venetian in order to have the early check in. We did the $20 sandwich between the photo id and the credit card and we asked for the highest floor possible with a beautiful view. The front desk clerk quickly says &quot;of course&quot; with a big smile. Our original reservation at the venetian was for a suite type: Venetian Rialto Suite - 2 Queen beds and after the $20 sandwich we got room#15-205 which was high enough to see part of the Mirage hotel, all of Treasure Island and all of Trump hotel and the hotel pools downstairs in the courtyard.Our room was next to storage rooms so it was very quiet all the time and plus we didn't see anyone coming or going during our four day stay here at this hotel on this particular floor. I quess either not many people know about the sandwich bribe or don't want to pay that extra money. On the print out reservation sheet it listed the suite types and it says that the &quot;Venetian Rialto View&quot; would cost -+$80 more per night because of the view, so i quess it was worth it.We room was very nice and spacious for my three kids to run around in, there were two 42&quot; or 50&quot; flat screen TV in the suite and one small flat screen TV in the bathroom. A remote control for the window curtains which is cool.The bathroom is bigger than an average size bedroom and the suite itself is approximately 1,300 SQ FT give and take.Our first night there, I insisted eating at Treasure Island cost us $66 and it's not worth it because the selection of food was not much to choose from.The next morning we decided to try the all day buffet at Excauliber, we thought it was 24hours buffet but it's only an all day buffet. So we paid and got the braclet at 10am and we can come back anytime to eat until 10pm that day.Travelling back and forth from the Venetian to the Excauliber took roughly 40 minutes each way even though we took the monorail as well. The monorail cost $13/person for 24hours unlimited and kids under 5 ride free.We got lost in Excauliber and a sales person approached us and asked if we were interested in buying one of the shows and that he would give us a good price for it.The catch was that we had to attend a 3-4hours timeshare presentation 15minutes outside of the strip. We were promised four tickets to see the &quot;Tournament of the kings&quot; for $50 upfront and we will receive the show tickets after we completed the presentation for the timeshare. If you buy the tickets at the Excauliber ticketing booth it would cost you $65/person which includes taxes. We thought it's a bargain, and I thought we were probably scammed or something. The sales agent asked a series of questions such as: are you a homeowner, are you married to each other, what family income, what citizen you are, if you read and write english and a few other questions. We showed up the next morning to get on the timeshare bus at the Exclauliber hotel and there were many other people that signed up too.When we got to the Grandview timeshare preview center we were each assigned to a sales agent, they were pressured to make the sales pitch.the mirror image side A and side B suite would cost $41,000 US and the monthly payments would be $2700/month. The next person they pass you onto was the sales manager and then another Co-op and then four hours later after you reject their sales pitch you wait out in another waiting room. Another person will ask you to fill out a questionaire before they issue you the tickets for the show that you wanted.Even though attending this timeshare presentation saved us $200 for the show to see the &quot;Tournament of the Kings&quot; but it was time consuming and you feel like the sales managers are very pushy and they make you go through so many people before you get the tickets. So if you don't mind wasting four hours of the vacation time and saving some money on the show otherwise don't go.The Tournament of the King was a dinner show set in med evil time in an oval arena where everyone sit and eat and enjoy the one and half hour show. They serve mugs of pop drinks, the entre is one small chicken with a few fries and a piece of brocoli and a sweet pie for dessert. The show overall was just okay but i wouldn't pay $65 per person to go see it.	
