Aug 26 2009 	Lovely stay	Our family stayed in two separate Bella Suites with a beautiful pool view. The room was large with an area for two queen beds and a sunken living room area. There are three TVs ... one in the living area, one in the bed area and one in the bathroom. The A/C in one of the room was not working but a call to the front desk resulted in a technician responding quickly to fix the issue.The beds and comforter were very comfy but the pillows were not as fluffy ... this is very noticeable because of the huge difference between the comforter and pillow. The housecleaning staff did a good job throughout our stay, although I did find a stray grape in the living room when we first checked in. The bathroom and toiletries provided is very nice.There are definitely lots of pools in the Venetian. There are couple of smaller pools by the Venezia Tower and couple of bigger pools in the main hotel. We used the bigger pools by the main hotel and found them very nice. There are also a few hot tubs but we did not use them. The towel service was good too. We had lots of fun playing in the pool and lounging by it.We hope to be back again soon.	
Aug 25 2009 	Deceptive advertising and the hotel is too big and confusing	Reserved the &quot;Suite Life&quot; package, which contains several included items. One is &quot;One American breakfast for two from In-Suite Dining.&quot; The hotel thinks that means, &quot;Only 1 breakfast, but you can share it with as many people as you want&quot; - even the one cup of coffee and one glass of juice! Was charged for the 2d breakfast; complained to front desk, which agreed with a laugh that this is silly and promised to delete it, but then the charge was still there when I checked out. Didn't try most of the other items, thank goodness. Who knows what deception may be in the others? Such nonsense from a hotel that otherwise has a decent rep for a big place on the strip.Oh, yes, it is big - Venetian, Palazzo, plus a third hotel called Venezia. The layout is very confusing - I've never met so many lost guests before in my life. Other issues - no tissues, no laundry bag, loose toilet seat/cover.All in all, I would say go to some other big resort. The deceptive advertising reveals a mean spirit that underlies the hotel's attitude toward its guests - &quot;There's one born every minute, let's take advantage of all of them.&quot;	
Aug 25 2009 	An Amazing Experience	We recently returned from a wonderful 3 night stay at the Venetian and were extremely please with our choice. We have previously stayed at several other resorts (our favorite being the Mirage), but decided to switch to the Venetian as this was a &quot;special&quot; Birthday trip for my partner. We booked under the special Summer promotion, receiving a rate of $149.00 per night. Check-In was not the lengthy process described by others. We arrived at 2:15 PM and the roped off check-in line was full. Every position at the front desk was manned, and our actual wait in line was 12 minutes. Our staff member, Jonathon James, was professional. courteous and had a great sense of humor.We had 2 rooms on the 20th floor (King/Non-Smoking) 3 doors from each other. Both overlooked the pool and Strip.Everything that has been said about the rooms is true. They are beautifully decorated, spotlessly clean, and huge. We especially loved the remote controlled electric shades and large bathroom.Maid service was never a problem, and our rooms were always cleaned before noon.Elevators were fast and plentiful. Rarely had to wait.The pool area is huge, and finding 4 chairs together was never a problem. In fact, people arriving at the pool around noon were still able to find chairs, even though the hotel itself was quite full.Yes, the hotel is crowded. Yes, you need to walk quite far to get anywhere. But, there is so much to see the time and distances pass quickly.Food and drinks are very expensive at the hotel, so be prepared to find some alternatives. For breakfast, there is a Denny's directly to the left of the hotel next to Sephora. Our 2 breakfasts cost as much as 1 omelet at the hotel.Our only complaint was the hideous perfume smell which permeates the Lobby as well as several areas on the ground level. It certainly is not subtle.We will certainly return to the Venetian and will highly recommend it to all of our friends. There is no reason to stay anywhere else.	
Aug 24 2009 	Bravo	Just walked in the door from driving back to Simi Valley CA from Vegas. My wife and I stayed at the Venetian for the first time. Our suite was in the Venezia Tower, which is actually pretty difficult to navigate your way to; everyone in the various elevators we were requited to take seemed to feel the same way. However, no one seemed particularly upset about the overall experience of being lost in the Venetian. The staff is immediately helpful and, this is just a guess, of course, are all on Effexor. The level of courteousness and good vibes that comes off the property’s staff is worth the price of admission. Then throw in the suites and all around convenience of the on-site amenities and there is just nothing to complain about. The only thing I might not want to do again room-wise is the “strip view.” Our view was across the breathtakingly beautiful condenser and tar covered roof of Bill’s Gambling Hall and across Las Vegas Blvd. to the Mirage, where, even from a bird’s eye perch on the fifth floor, the volcano looks like a questionable use of gas. I think there are pool veiw rooms and we may go that way next time.The bed was great, the pillows a little harder than I like, but now I’m just nit-picking. The bathroom was bigger than some entire rooms I’ve stayed in (but I'm paroled now and I'm clean - kidding of course), and was very nicely appointed (I’m not even exactly sure what “nicely appointed” means, but if they were giving this room away on a game show, I’m certain that’s what they would call it.)We didn’t see any of the shows on the property, but both “Love” and “Mystere” from Cirque Du Solieil are walking distance across the street. We’ve seen Mystere twice and saw Love last night. Both are unthinkably good. And, consider this while you’re watching; the casts of these shows don’t change from performance to performance or even night to night; they are the SAME people performing these spectacles twice a night five nights a week! It's mind blowing. And since the Phantom playing at the Venetian is the Hal Prince directed staging, which I’ve seen elsewhere, I can tell you that’s great, too! We don’t really gamble, but I can tell you that the Dean Martin one cent slot has the best music.Since we caught a mercifully cool if cloudy day and didn’t feel much like being inert, I can’t report much on the pools, save to say that the Venezia Tower has its own small pool/garden and it’s great. And, right there with its outdoor seating area on the deck of the pool, sits Bouchon, which is THE place to have breakfast or on Sundays; brunch. They serve other meals but we didn’t try them so I can’t comment. Breakfast however, rocks. The pastries are key to an enjoyable visit and, if you just want to grab a sandwich and some amazing deserty something, there’s a Bouchon bakery at the Casino level in the Venetian. Such great stuff!&quot;Zine&quot; the inventively decorated Chinese restaurant at the Palazzo doesn’t use MSG. That’s about all I can say about it. It was pretty mediocre for us though in their defense, we were only having Dim Sum appetizers. Overall, our visit to the Venetian was great and we would not hesitate to stay there again. I am checking my email for some kind ‘invite you back’ promotion right now!	
