Aug 11 2009 	Wish we'd stayed elsewhere	From the moment you arrive and follow the bizarre and lengthy trek from the parking garage to the front desk (go to this elevator bank, switch over, walk here, walk there - is there not a better way?! Obviously this is not an issue for those who are cabbing it to and from the front doors, but what about the rest of us?), the stay goes downhill. First, you are allergenically assaulted by the most vile, cloying, syrupy-thick, fake &quot;floral&quot; scent you'll ever experience. Be prepared to cough, sneeze and wipe your watery eyes while you wait 30+ minutes in the lobby to check in. Once you finally arrive at the desk, the disinterested, &quot;hurry up, I'm bored&quot;, lackluster demeanor from the folks behind the counter really make you feel unwelcome, as though THEY are doing YOU a favor by &quot;allowing&quot; you to stay at their property. We did not have the same issue concerning the key as many others have, but I could see others around us at the desk complaining about that. Never were we greeted by name or shown any appreciation for our business. I can excuse a LOT of oversight in lieu of good service experiences at a hotel; unfortunately, the Venetian lacks service wholly and completely. Once we dragged our bags down the long hike through the casino, around to the elevators, and up to the 9th floor (no bellhop was ever offered), we found the suite to be clean and in fairly good condition. However, we discovered items missing from the minibar and called the desk to avoid being charged. After 7 mins. on hold (really?! 7 minutes to reach a human?!) before even speaking to anyone, we requested that the items be removed from the account. We were assured our account was noted. Flash forward to check out, not only were the items NOT removed, there were ADDITIONAL items charged for which we had to argue over to get taken off the bill. In any event, the suites are spacious and well-appointed; no complaints there. They are not real big on providing you with even 1 extra towel or a bar of soap, however. You have to ask. And then wait a long time for the towels to arrive. The common areas are of course smoky - I'm a smoker so it didn't bother me, but my husband is not - but more so, they seem to have a &quot;dusty&quot; feel to them. I don't know how else to describe it. At no time during our stay did any Venetian staffer greet us, show any kind of interest in our business or exhibit even the most basic friendly courtesies. The same included for Club Grazie. Why existing members have to wait in line AN HOUR to pick up their card behind new sign-ups is beyond me!! How about 2 separate lines, folks?? In any event...we went to other hotels on the strip for various activities and shows, and the services there were stellar - and they knew we weren't even guests at their properties. As for navigating this mammoth property...understand that the Venetian/Palazzo is ENORMOUS. It would take you days and a guided tour to figure out where everything is. That's fine, but it seems they could have laid out the floor plan a little better and more efficiently. Nonetheless, the service issues were the big problem for us. And PS, what's with no coffee makers in the rooms?? That's just BASIC, Motel 6 kind of stuff!! And the business center...$7.50 to print a boarding pass??? Really?? As for the CROWDS...if you like loud, cackling, *extremely* intoxicated 20-somethings falling down around you and dumping their drinks in the Casino and restaurants, generally causing a spectacle, then you will like the vibe in the Venetian. I certainly wasn't expecting a church retreat and I like late night partying as much as the next person, but I was indeed expecting a higher class of people at the Venetian. Like I said, I would overlook a lot of physical shortcomings at a hotel in lieu of service-oriented care and/or a property that seemed to give a damn that we were paying guests. The Venetian may look pretty at the outset, but the experience is sorely lacking. Would not recommend or stay there again. Next time, we'll do the Bellagio, which is where we were originally booked. I wish I hadn't changed the reservation.	
