Aug 10 2009 	Luxury and elegance	The suites at the Venetian are huge and luxurious, and furnished traditionally, but the decor is bright enough for them not to feel too old fashioned. Nothing is stinted on, except perhaps lighting, but you don't go to Vegas to read in your room. It will take you the first 24 hours to find your way around the hotel. It becomes easier when you realise that there are three parts to it - the Venetian Tower, The Venezia Tower, and the Pallazio. We arrived around midnight and were checked in within minutes. Be prepared for a long queue if you check in during the day. Checking out during the day was very quick and we were offered storage for our luggage, which we declined because we didn't have long to wait for our pick-up. We sat out the time in the casino food court. There was a charge to our account for phone calls but the receptionist noticed that these were local and removed it.Many of the hotels on the Strip have their own theme, and our main reason for choosing the Venetian was to experience its canals, shops and gondolas. We don't regret our choice, and will always carry with us the memory of the fake sky, perpetual dusk and sparkling blue water that can't be the least bit reminiscent of Venice itself but are a good make-believe substitute that typifies the whole Vegas experience. Go with a sense of fun and you'll love it.	
