Aug 3 2009 	Beautiful hotel services understaffed	Went for hubby's 50th birthday. The lobby is spectacular. We arrived around midnight and they had an accordian player still in the lobby. Check-in was about 10 min. probably due to the late hour. (Note: A visit to the Luxor revealed the horror that Vegas hotel check-in could have been. I strongly recommend you arrive off hours.)The check-in service was OK, if a bit rushed. All staff behind the desk were young, maybe early 20's. The girl that checked us in told us 10th floor, room 408. She neglected to mention that the elevator from the lobby to the Venezia section arrives on the 10th floor, evne though it's only 1 floor up. So, as a result, we went up to what we thought was the 10th floor, only to discover someone in that room already. Back to the elevators, where we checked with a guard. Turns out, we were on that 1st(?) level. The rooms in this wing are beatuiful and large. There were some minor imperfections, such as a missing cacbinet handle, hooks missing/broken from the curtains due to misuse. The mattress was a bit hard, so we asked to look at another room. They gave us a look at the other tower (Fogrget the name), but we did not like that room at all. The decor was more modern instead of classic, the roman shade couldn't be raised, and we hated the dark and dreary color scheme and modern lights. So back to the 1st room and the hard bed. Turned out it wasn't that bad.The garden pool is beautifully designed, lots of shade. I assume other reveiws about misbehavior at the pool referred to the large pool. Everyone here was well behaved, with the exception of one couple on their honeymoon in the small hottub, which everyone avoided due to potential embarrasment. The concierge on our floor was most helpful, and there wasn't a line. We purchased the resort package - $20 food coupon, spa/gym use, free wax museum entry (cost - $25), and $15 credit in slots - for $30 a piece. Used everything but the gym, so was a good deal. Ate at Bouchon twice and enjoyed the food. The sit down resaturants are pricey, but servings are large. There is a food court, and a McD's within walking distance if necessary. There is also a Walhgreen's pharmacy right next door. Patrons: There were what I assume to be a lot of bridal parties there. Most of the young women were thin and dressed in short dresses and high heels, but not tacky. The rest of the patrons were fairly normal, but slightly higher class dress than across the street at the Mirage or T.I. The table minimums seemed to keep a good deal of the riff raff out of the casino, although there are a few penny slots. We did notice some rather roudy girls trying to get into our hallway, but the guard would not let them through. There were plenty of guards around the hallways and even the shops, more than I've seen at other hotels. This seems to be the one area of staff that the hotel is not skimping on, thank goodness. A couple of the patrons were drinking at the garden pool with alcohol they brought form their minibar (I assume), but they did not get out of hand. Shopping: Had a blast here. The inside shops on the way to the Palazzo shops run along a fake canal, where you can do the inside gondola rides (Too hot to do the outside version during the day). Most of the casinos now have these Oxygen bars = $22 for 15 min of O2, and you get a back massage, short scalp massage, and some electircal stimulus. OK, so they are trying to sell their gadgets, but for us, the massage helped, and the scented O2 cleared our sinuses. Plus it was a chance to sit down and relax, so we didn't mind the cost. The hotel version of St. Mark's Sq has several restaurants, and usually has a few street performers in period costume. If you continue to follow the hallway along the left hand side of the square, you will come out into the Palazzo shops, an entirely different mall. Eventually you get to the Palazzo's casino.We didn't see any shows at the V this time, but have seen Blue Man Group before, which I recommend if you like general sillyness and don't take yourself too seriously. Checkout was online. I made a small error and blew through the screen too fast, but when I called to ask for a detailed breakdown, they were happy to emial one to me, in addition to telling me the prices on the phone. Yes, there was a bit of a wait each time we called the front desk. Also, they were kind enough to give us a late checkout of 1pm. We used the concierge for airline check in, and were informed that the USAIR desk downstairs could check our bags directly to the flight for a fee. Of course, the $20 fee is on top of the airline's baggage fee. We were going to use it, but when we talked to the young man at the desk, he neglected to mention that his desk closed at 3pm - our flight was at midnight. So, we saved some money. The bell stations held our bags for us until we were ready to leave.We visited the T.I. and the Luxor this trip. I wouldn't stay at either, but I'm getting to teh age where I'd rather pay extra for shorter waits.So, overall, we liked the hotel. The decorations are wonderful and were the highlight of the stay. Loved the Garden Pool. Would stay at the V again, but only if we could stay in the same section of the hotel near the Garden Pool.	
