Jul 29 2009 	Five Diamonds? I don't think so.	After returning from a recent weekend visit to the Venetian, I can honestly say there are much better five diamond hotels on the Vegas strip. For the same cost, the Bellagio and the Wynn are much better alternatives to the Venetian. And unlike the Venetian, those hotels treat you like a valued guest. If the Venetian was a three diamond hotel, it would explain the condition of the rooms and the disrespectful way in which we were treated. For a five diamond, there is no excuse.Highlights of the things that soured our experience are as follows:1. Cattle call check in and pure chaos when we arrived – It was clear that the desk attendants were trying to get everyone through the line as quickly is possible, which I appreciate, but not at the expense of making your hotel guests feel like they don’t matter.2. Newly programmed key cards that don’t work on the door – We had four keys. Two of them worked.3. Worn condition of rooms – The rooms have definitely seen better days. There were stains on our couch and missing buttons. The lighting was so dim, even with all the lights on. We found face wash cloths from previous guests hanging on our door, and the bathroom door wouldn’t close.4. Disrespectful staff – My husband and I are in our twenties, which is the only reason I can think of that would explain why we were repeatedly treated by hotel staff like we couldn’t possibly be guests there. The funny thing is, the Venetian isn’t any more pricey than the Bellagio or the Wynn and both those places make us feel welcome. I don’t know why the Venetian is so full of themselves. They required we show our hotel room cards before charging to our room and before we could enter the elevators to go up to our room. I understand and appreciate security measures, but there is a nice way to do it, and there is a mean way to do it. They consistently approached us like we couldn’t afford to be guests there until we flashed our card. I was even ID’d before I could charge to our room for breakfast. The funny thing about that is that at that particular restaurant, you HAVE to be a hotel guest to even get into the restaurant!5. Being charged for “free” breakfast – Our package included daily complimentary breakfast for two. We called to confirm it was for two people prior to placing our order. They assured us it was. Then they charged us $27 for our free breakfast. We had to dispute the claim during check out, which meant standing in the long check out line instead of being able to use the television check out. While the front desk attendant was nice, she couldn’t/wouldn’t take the charge off and made us file a complaint with guest services. Two weeks later and we still haven’t gotten a response from them. 6. Waiting on hold – Waiting ten minutes on hold just to reach someone at the front desk is not acceptable for a five diamond hotel.None of the above-mentioned complaints ruined our weekend, but knowing that for the same amount of money, we can stay at a hotel that truly makes us feel like guests, there is no reason to ever return to the Venetian. What a disappointment!	
