Jul 23 2009 	Nice Rooms - Scary Environment	Just returned from a 3-night stay at the Venetian with my elderly mother and her friend in mid-July. Even though rates were low (it was mid-July after all) I expected a luxury hotel experience - I couldn't have been more wrong.We had two rooms, and both were nice in size and furnishings. My mother's room had a broken safe, however. I asked that it be fixed when we arrived...it was never fixed. Fortunately we could all use the safe in my room, but I do expect better from a good hotel.Cleaning was another issue. My room was cleaned properly every day. My mother's room (a more expensive room) was never properly cleaned, and cleaned only when we asked a maid to clean it. The beds were never made. We had to ask for clean towels from the housecleaner's cart. And this room was only 4 doors away from my room - another issue since we had requested adjacent or adjoining rooms and they were unable to accomodate us.The staff in general was rude and unhelpful. Checkin involved a half-hour wait in a Disney-style snaking line; not a luxury hotel experience. Check out was worse. There was no electronic checkout available via TV, no ability to view your bill. So I went to check out at the front desk at 6:30 am to avoid the crowds. There were 10 people in line, and only one person at the front desk. This for a huge hotel?? One person in line called the hotel on his cell phone to request more help...after about 15 minutes another person showed up at the front desk. By then it was 7am and the line was much longer. Really inexcusably bad.But the worst part of the hotel was the scary environment and clientele. We were staying in the Venetian tower, which is adjacent to the Grand Canal food court and self-parking garage. This might be the reason for the bad crowds we encountered. There was a security guard posted at the elevator entry on both the casino level and the Grand Canal/food court level. I was grateful for this - although the guards paid little attention to who came and went, at least they were there as a deterrent. There were large crowds of rowdy young people in this area. Now, I know Las Vegas has lots of rowdy young people everywhere...but many of them here were people I would certainly not want to meet alone in a hotel corridor. Drunk kids are an inconvenience....these were not just drunk kids...they were the sort of people I'd expect to find in 'bad' areas of US cities, hanging around in groups. Perhaps it's because the tower is adjacent to the free parking garage, but I was very uncomfortable walking to our rooms, particularly with my elderly mother. I've stayed in lots of Vegas hotels - Mandalay, Monte Carlo, MGM, Mirage, Caesar's- and once had the misfortune of getting stuck in the Excalibur when there were no other rooms in town during a big trade show. The Venetian rooms were nice, but the crowd in our area of the hotel was worse than I've ever experienced at any other Vegas hotel - even the Excalibur. I should add that crowds in other areas of the hotel did not seem to be the same type of people...but it was scary around the Venetian tower. If you do decide to stay at the Venetian, suggest you request a room elsewhere.	
Jul 23 2009 	Almost Perfect	We visited Vegas over the Juy 4th weekend with friends for a wedding. We decided on The Venetian because we got a great deal and we heard so many positive reviews. We booked a Luxury View Suite. Our stay was nearly perfect in every way: quick check-in, superb accommodations, excellent service, great food and just about everything you could want in a hotel. The staff were friendly and we had absolutely not one problem; however, our time in the hotel was almost unbearable due to the floral fragrance. I had read about it and thought it a silly complaint. When we stepped into the elevator in the parking garage my husband started coughing. He coughed nearly the entire time we were in the Venetian for 5 days/4 nights. He was highly allergic to whatever they are pumping throughout the entire hotel. He hasn't had anything like this happen to him before. It bothered me as well, but I had no physical reaction. We bought cough syrup at the Walgreen's, which helped him sleep at night. It was almost comical each day as soon as we stepped out of the Venetian he was fine and the moment he returned it all started up again. Our friends couldn't believe it! He had no issues at any other casino we visited over the weekend. It is such a shame because the hotel is perfect in every other way. If we return to Vegas we unfortunately can't stay here again.	
Jul 23 2009 	Venetian - The Good and Bad	VENETIAN HOTEL &amp; CASINO (July 20-23, 2009) THE GOOD The Offer: We stayed at the Venetian Hotel Casino, July 20 through 23, 2009, for a $129.00 special rate per night that included a luxury suite at The Venetian or Palazzo, two tickets to Phantom of the Opera, 20% off on several fine dining restaurants, 2-for-1 drinks at one lounge, $50 of an 80-minute spa service and $25 in Free Slot Play. We usually stay at Mandalay Bay in the regular deluxe rooms or one bedroom suites for $99 a night but could not pass up the Phantom tickets included with the Venetian stay. The Room: We stayed in the Venetian Tower. We were on the 14th Floor near the end of a very long hallway. The room was just like it was advertised. There was a pedestal type bed in one semi-loft section followed by a second area two steps down that included an L-shaped couch, desk, and table and chairs. It was 110 degrees outside and we set the thermostat to 65 and it kept the room chilly. Amenities: The room lacked amenities in the bath, so when we called for bar soap to be sent up to the room. We were sent a full double package of amenities with four soaps, two shampoos and conditioners, and two lotions. (But we should not have to ask.) It arrived within ten minutes of calling which was exceptionally quick for any hotel service to the room, plus there was a follow-up message on the phone making sure it arrived. That’s good customer service. In Room Dining Card: There is an in-room dining card for breakfast (similar to hospital cards you fill out for your meals for the next day) hanging on the inside door knob. You can fill it out, leave it on the outer door knob and breakfast can be ordered in advance for delivery the next morning by simply selecting your breakfast, delivery time and hanging it on the knob prior to 1:00 AM. The pricing is similar to other hotels. Bath: Like most of the newer or remodeled hotels, the bath has a separate shower and large size tub, which is nice. Shopping: Just outside the elevator area to the rooms, there is a coffee kiosk that has the best mochas I’ve ever tasted. It’s pricey but good. They also carry sandwiches which they will heat for you ($10.99) and an assortment of gourmet breakfast rolls, fruit cups, brownies, donuts, etc (about $4-$8 each) that are absolutely delicious. The Grand Canal Shoppes and Shoppes at Palazzo are close by (just up the escalators from the room elevators on the ground floor). The shops are pricey and geared for anorexics, but if you shop the discount racks you can find some deals. They have some wonderfully unique shops if you are looking for something special including a Brookstone store. They also have another Food Court and some Coffee Bean Tea kiosks. THE EXCELLENT The Phantom Tickets: Since two tickets were free with the room, I expected the tickets to be in the nose bleed section where everyone looked like ants on stage. I was greatly surprised to find we were offered a seating chart and large choice of seats that included both side areas with seats all the way down to the stage in addition to the mezzanine above. The seats we chose usually sell for $137 each. I expected to pay an upgrade charge for anything other than nose bleed seats. Our tickets were in Section 3, Aisle L, seats 63 and 64. That’s stage left near the aisle between the left and center sections about 11 rows from the front. So cool! It cancelled out all the little negativities that we experienced. In Room Office: In the desk area there was a combination fax, scan, copier and printer. You need to bring your own paper, but this was an exceptional extra. The biggest bonus was a power strip with five empty plugs right beside the desk. No hunting for a place to plug in your laptop or cell phone chargers (Yay!). I couldn’t figure out the free internet but didn’t really need it so I didn’t bother calling down to get it hooked up. Two Phones: There were two wireless telephones in the room with stations by the bed and the desk. You could keep a phone beside you and you didn’t have to jump up to answer it. Wake-Up Calls: The Wake-Up Call is a live person not automated. We were awakened by a very pleasant female voice which told us the time, temperature outside and asked if there was anything else they could do for us. THE BAR  Bell Service: When we arrived about 1:00 PM, we parked in Valet as we usually do and waited for a Bell Hop to take the luggage. The Valet Ticket Handler called several times for bell service. After ten minutes of waiting, a Bell Hop came over, told the Valet Ticket Holder that he was leaving for lunch and he left. No one else came. The Valet apologized and we dragged our luggage in ourselves. Check-In: The line for check in was about 25 people long (but went very quickly – maybe 10 minutes) and the lobby was overfilled with noisy people waiting for “something.” We told the check in rep that we couldn’t get Bell Service at Valet. She apologized, gave us our room keys and but still did not call Bell Service to the desk to assist with our luggage. So we dragged our luggage through the casino to our elevators, and then to our rooms. It was a very long walk and our arms were about to fall off by the time we arrived at our rooms. It was very noisy in the lobby during check-in and we could not understand hardly anything the check-in rep said even though we asked her to speak up. She just continued to mumble and look downward as she spoke. She handed us our paperwork including a keyholder card but forgot to place our room keys inside it and had to call us back. Recommendation: Always ask for rooms close to the elevator. Amenities: We were told the room was ready but when we arrived there were no amenities like hand soap. We had to call down to the Front Desk and ask for some hand soap to be sent up. Prior to that, we attempted to get a bar of soap from the housekeeping staff who were still cleaning rooms on the floor, but not one of them spoke English and didn’t have a clue what we asking for even though we pantomimed in addition to asking. Lighting: My biggest complaint would be the lack of lighting in the room. I’m older (56) and need some bright lighting to see well. Even with all the lights in the room on and the blinds completely open the room was still darkened. Plus it took me a while to find all the light switches. Food: All the food was terribly over-priced, even the Food Courts. In the Casino Food Court: a slice of pizza and drink was $15; a sandwich with fries and a drink was $22; and the Shoppes Food Court: two rice bowls at the fast food kiosk without drinks was $16. If you ate at the Café it was about $40 for two people. We purchased some snacks at the Walgreen's store close by (which was also way over-priced) to offset food charges and paid $5.99 for a 12-pack of Pepsi and $5 for chips. The other restaurants ranged from $25 to $150 per person so the small discount coupons were practically useless. Player’s Club: It’s called the Grazie Club, and new players can get $25 in Free Slot Play. The cards come with pretty gold chains attached that are short and completely useless for remembering to take the card with you from slot to slot. The line for cards was always 20-30 people long each time we checked throughout the day. We finally just got in line and endured the wait. There were four reps working, but it still took 35 minutes to get the cards. Recommendation: Ask for four cards and put the extras in your wallet or purse so you don’t have to stand in line again. Slot Play: The slots are so tight they squeak. I’m a local and we play at a different casino almost every month. Recommendation: Stay at the Venetian but play slots across the street at Treasure Island where the slots are loose. Do not stay at Treasure Island, it’s a dump and the workers are rude, but the slots pay pretty well. Room Layout: The room has two large screen plasma TVs but the TVs are only 15 feet apart with no dividing wall, so if both TVs are on, they have to be set to the same station or hearing them is impossible. Also, a good change would be track drapes for the bed area to close off the bed area from the livingroom area so early sleepers can go to bed and not be disturbed by the lights and TV. Bath: They only leave a few towels and rags, not really enough for even two people. Plus there’s no where to hang up a wet rag or towel to dry and the counter space is minimal for setting up hot hair setters and make-up. Window Coverings: This is probably just my bad … but it took me 20 minutes to figure out how to open and close the window covering. I finally realized there was a remote control on the wall in the bedroom area, 20-feet away from the window, by the thermostat, which controlled the curtains. Ice Machines: The ice machines are located behind a door with a small “Ice” sign just off the circular lobby on each floor. It’s kind of hard to find if you don’t know where to look. If your room is down the hall, and ours was way down the hall, it’s a bit of a hike just for ice. Recommendation: Carry some gallon size Ziplocs in your purse and grab ice as you travel back to the room. Valet Car Pick-Up: We retrieved our vehicle about 1:00PM to go to another casino to gamble for better slot payback. When we gave valet the ticket, we were told it would be a 20-30 minute wait for the car. That is a ridiculous amount of time to wait for a car. No other casino has ever made us wait that long. It was a full 25 minutes waiting in 106 degree heat with 55% humidity before the car arrived. Recommendation: During the summer months, carry a personal mister with you while in Vegas. OVERALL: Since we were comped tickets with the room offer, it was a great deal. But if the tickets had not been included I would rather stay at Mandalay Bay THEhotel in a one bedroom suite for their ongoing special price of $99 a night weekdays. You get more room for a lower price (two queen beds, separate livingroom area and two bathrooms), valet offers you a bottle of ice cold water when you check in and out, the service is always exceptional and the slots are looser. We’ve stayed there a dozen times or more and have been very pleased. Even the deluxe rooms are large, the beds are divine, and the deluxe rooms have two large closets and a huge bath area, plus the food court and some of the restaurants are reasonable.	
