Jul 10 2009 	Five Diamond no more?	Just returned from a four- day stay at The Venetian in Las Vegas. I make it a point to review comments on Tripadvisor before staying at any hotel, and I must admit I was a little nervous after reading The Venetian reviews. First, I am glad to say my experience was better than expected, but not necessarily excellent. Let me qualify that I travel a lot for work and fun, and spend a fair amount of time in Las Vegas, so I’m not new to the market. My room was 27-366, a 1,300 sqft+ Piazza Suite on the 27th floor of the hotel, for which I got a great rate; so nothing to complain about. The room was spacious with a large foyer and powder room, a dining room, large living room, bedroom and master bathroom. It had 3 LCD televisions, 3 phones, a fax and printer, a mini fridge and a mini-bar (Be aware that when you move anything around in the mini-bar you will get charged. There is however a very clear sign on the fridge to let you know that), a safe, a wet bar and a cd player/clock radio. The room appears not to have been updated since the property was built in 1999 and it showed its age; however the room was clean and adequately stocked with fresh towels and wonderful toiletries.My arrival experience was nothing special. I pulled up to valet at a very busy time. The valet attendant was friendly but it took about 15 minutes for my car to be moved. It took that much time also to make it to check-in. Not a big deal; I sort of expect that in Las Vegas. While waiting however, another valet who was stiffed on a tip walked by me and loudly stated a profanity, which was a bit shocking to say the least. Check-in was very busy but it took only about 15 minutes to get checked in. The front desk staff was friendly and no issues there; although at check-out we realized they had overcharged my credit card (more later). They offered an additional upgrade to a larger suite, but since I already booked a larger suite I declined the offer. Finding your room elevators can be a bit of an adventure when checking in for the first time. The Venetian and Palazzo complex is I believe the biggest hotel in the world with 7,000+ rooms, which makes the property a monster. It took us about 20 minutes to make it from the front desk to our room. Getting to your room you have to pass through a “security station“staffed by a “costumed” security person checking to make sure you have a room key. Even though this gives you a certain sense of security, the attitude of the guards are not necessarily the best. I can’t recall a single time walking through the area and receiving a friendly “hello”; most of the times you get the image of an annoyed person passing the time doing a job. Speaking of room keys; our door was really hard to open. It took several times each time to open our door. Sort of annoying! I had read many horror stories about housekeeping on Tripadvisor; we really didn’t have a big issue. I can only imagine the challenge of keeping a hotel of this size up to par. In general housekeeping staff was friendly, saying “hi” in the hallways and when servicing the room did the job right. My first day there we went to breakfast around 9am and there was a note on our door already that housekeeping had already stopped by and if we wanted them to come by later we had to call, which we did. It seemed a bit early. On our last day we had removed the “do not disturb” sign from our door. In general housekeeping knocks before coming in, here the person simply opened our door and walked in while we were getting ready. The bed linens were clean and crisp, however one of the sheets on our king size bed had a hole in it. It was not replaced during our stay. We also did not have a laundry bag in any of the closets in the room. If you have an opportunity to see a show, see “Phantom of the Opera” at the resort. The setting is beautiful and the show is worth every penny. From the sets, the costumes and especially the talent, hats off. Prices for refreshments at the show are Vegas high with a small bottle of water costing $6 and a diet soda $5. I had read some horror stories on valet parking. Aside of the earlier mentioned experience valet staff was friendly and efficient. My shortest wait was about 10 minutes, my longest 20. Due to the size of Vegas hotels there is always a bit of a wait at valet, as long as you know that, the wait isn’t bad.Usually I check out in my room. This process did not work for us and we had to go to check out in person. The line was long but we were able to check out in about 10 minutes. The reason I was not able to check out in the room is that a mistake was made upon check-in. My credit card was overcharged and a refund had to be processed in person. The front desk person was surprised by the mistake but managed the check out process and refund with a smile. We also learned the reason we were not able to charge anything to our room. At check-in our information was entered incorrectly resulting in errors when we tried to charge.We had an issue with the in-room safe. It would not lock. We called service and within 15 minutes a service person showed up and fixed the issue. Turn-down service seems to be included but it is not; if you require the service you need to call. All in all my experience at The Venetian wasn’t a bad one, but I expect more from a 5 Diamond property in service, room style, attention to detail and overall experience.	
