 hotel tried to charge me OVER $500/night for most of my stay. The rate we had booked was about $139/night. At first I thought maybe it was just a snafu with me but then I saw a couple of my collegues walking past and they told me and the desk that they'd had the same issue. When I called our corporate travel office they gave me the correct rate but the hotel desk &quot;manager&quot; at first hid from the call and then when I persisted told me he'd fix it. He dodged me for so long that 1st evening that my iPhone battery ran down as the travel office waited on the line as the rest fo the desk staff would &quot;try&quot; to locate him and get him on the call. eventually out of exhaustion and with a dead battery I checked in and they charged my card the FULL amount for the week. He just kept ducking me and our corporate office for almost 3 days. Eventually the Venetian backed out the fake charges but I had to spend over 3 hours on the phone with everyone involved to get it fixed. I asked for nothing but the rate I booked and told them I wanted no comps or anything I wanted very much to be respectful and make the point that i was going to have none of their Las Vegas Shenanigans. I was there to work and wasn't looking for a handout all I wanted them to do was get their act together and it was painful. Even though I took no comps or other discounts they did send me a $100 food and beverage credit for the frustration. I still feel I'd have been ahead giving the front desk the $100 if they didn't make me spend 3 hours onthe phone. They are nice folks but are a stubborn lot on the rate mistake issue. i realize that they get a lot of drunken con artist customers trying to take advantage of them but I would respectfully ask that they be a little more willing to not force their convention crowd who's companies are spending millions of dollars/week to rent their facilities to get worn down by this sort of thing. It can leave a bad taste. I like their hotel and their staff in general could not be better or nicer. But to be more successful their staff &amp; their custoemrs deserve a better rate validation policy.	
